<div style1>
  <p><strong> Marxism and Critical Theory: a reading list Dr Drew Milne </strong></p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p> The core orientation text for this course is <em>Marxist Literary Theory: A Reader</em>, eds. Terry Eagleton and Drew Milne (Oxford: Blackwell, 1996). Also useful is <em>Modern Critical Thought: An Anthology of Theorists writing on Theorists</em> (Oxford: Blackwell, 2003), ed. Drew Milne Although less explicitly addressed to Marxism, this anthology provides a number of intersections between Marxism and critical theory, and supplementary reading suggestions. The following indications for core reading provide starting points for further reading. </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Session 1: Approaches to reading Marx and / or Marxism: </strong></p>
  <p> a) George Lukacs, &lsquo;What is Orthodox Marxism?&rsquo;, <em>History and Class Consciousness</em>, trans. Rodney Livingstone (London: Merlin, 1971), pp. 1-26 </p>
  <p> b) Jacques Derrida, <em>Specters of Marx</em>, trans. Peggy Kamuf (London: Routledge, 1994), esp. pp. 3-48 </p>
  <p> c) Michel Henry, <em>Marx: A Philosophy of Human Reality</em>, trans. Kathleen McLaughlin (Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1983) &ndash; abridged translation of two vol French work.; nb. esp. &lsquo;Introduction: The Theory of Marx&rsquo;s Texts&rsquo;, pp. 1-16 </p>
  <p><strong>Session 2: Early Marx and critical theory </strong></p>
  <p> a) Karl Marx, &lsquo;Contribution to the Critique of Hegel&rsquo;s Philosophy of Right&rsquo; and &lsquo;Economic and Philosophical Manuscripts&rsquo;, from <em>Early Writings</em>, ed. Tom Bottomore, pp. 243-258, pp. 279-400. There&rsquo;s a useful introduction by Lucio Colletti in this edition. </p>
  <p> b) Herbert Marcuse, &lsquo;Foundations of Historical Materialism&rsquo;, in <em>From Luther to Popper</em>, trans. Joris De Bres (London: Verso, 1983) &ndash; also published as <em>Studies in Critical Philosophy</em> (1972), pp. 1-48 </p>
  <p> c) Georg Lukacs, &lsquo;The Phenomenon of Reification&rsquo; (1922), from &lsquo;Reification and the Consciousness of the Proletariat&rsquo;, <em>History and Class Consciousness</em>, trans. Rodney Livingstone (London: Merlin Press, 1971), pp., 83-110, also, <em>Modern Critical Thought</em>, pp. 23-45. </p>
  <p><strong>Session 3: Classical Marxism and Marxist literary criticism </strong></p>
  <p> a) Marx and Engels, extracts from <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 30-41 </p>
  <p> b). V.I. Lenin, &lsquo;Leo Tolstoy and His Epoch&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 25-42 </p>
  <p> c). Leon Trotsky, &lsquo;The Formalist School of Poetry and Marxism&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 46-59 </p>
  <p> d). V.N. Volosinov, &lsquo;Concerning the Relationship of the Basis and Superstructures&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 60-68 </p>
  <p> e). Georg Lukacs, &lsquo;The Ideology of Modernism&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 141-162. </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Session 4: Aesthetics, Politics &amp; Modernity: Brecht / Benjamin / Adorno </strong></p>
  <p><strong> Core reading: </strong> (all from <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>) </p>
  <p> a). Walter Benjamin, &lsquo;Surrealism: The Last Snapshot of the European Intelligentsia&rsquo;, pp. 70-80; and &lsquo;Addendum to &ldquo;The Paris of the Second Empire in Baudelaire&rdquo;&rsquo;, pp. 80-3 </p>
  <p> b). Ernst Bloch, &lsquo;Marxism and Poetry&rsquo;, pp. 84-90 </p>
  <p> c) Bertolt Brecht, &lsquo;A Short Organum for the Theatre&rsquo;, pp. 107-135 </p>
  <p> d) Roland Barthes, &lsquo;The Tasks of Brechtian Criticism&rsquo;, pp. 136-140 </p>
  <p> e) T.W.Adorno, &lsquo;Commitment&rsquo;, pp. 187-203 (among other things, Adorno on Brecht) </p>
  <p><strong> &nbsp;</strong></p>
  <p> The readings from the anthology overlap with the readings in <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em> which is most rewarding when read as a whole. In addition to the above, you might usefully explore: </p>
  <p> a) Georg Lukacs, &lsquo;Realism in the Balance&rsquo;, <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, pp. 28-59 </p>
  <p> b) Bertolt Brecht, &lsquo;Against Georg Lukacs&rsquo;, <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, pp. 68-85 </p>
  <p> c) Walter Benjamin, &lsquo;Conversations with Brecht&rsquo;, <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, pp. 86-99 </p>
  <p> d) Theodor Adorno, &lsquo;Letters to Walter Benjamin&rsquo;, <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, pp. 110-133 </p>
  <p> e) Walter Benjamin, &lsquo;Reply&rsquo;, <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, pp. 134-141 </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Session 5: The Althusserian moment: ideology, &lsquo;theory&rsquo; and interpretation </strong></p>
  <p> a) Louis Althusser, &lsquo;Ideology and Ideological State Apparatuses (notes towards an Investigation)&rsquo;, <em>Mapping Ideology</em>, pp. 100-140; also in Louis Althusser, <em>Essays on Ideology</em> (London: Verso, 1984) and widely reproduced elsewhere </p>
  <p> b) Etienne Balibar and Pierre Macherey, &lsquo;On Literature as an Ideological Form&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 275-95 </p>
  <p> c) Terry Eagleton, &lsquo;Towards a Science of the Text&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 296-327, selected from <em>Criticism and Ideology</em>. </p>
  <p> d) Fredric Jameson, &lsquo;On Interpretation&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 351-374 </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Session 6: Post-Marxism?: post-modernism, irony and solidarity </strong></p>
  <p> a) Frederic Jameson, &lsquo;Postmodernism, or the Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism&rsquo;, <em>New Left Review</em>, 146 (1984); also as Chapter 1 of Fredric Jameson, <em>Postmodernism, Or, The Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism</em> (London: Verso, 1991). [Jameson&rsquo;s most important revisions of the 1980s essay are also suggested in &lsquo;Secondary Elaborations&rsquo;, <em>Postmodernism, </em>pp. 297-418.] </p>
  <p> b) Alex Callinicos, &lsquo;The Jargon of Postmodernity&rsquo;, <em>Marxist Literary Theory</em>, pp. 408-428 </p>
  <p> c) Judith Butler, Ernesto Laclau and Slavoj Zizek, <em>Contigency, Hegemony, Universality: Contemporary Dialogues on the Left</em> (London: Verso, 2000) </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Basic resources: </strong></p>
  <p> &lt;http://www.marxists.org&gt; &ndash; excellent website, with texts, archives, search engines for phrases in the complete works of Marx and other useful resources.<strong></strong></p>
  <p> Lee Baxandall, ed. <em>Marxism and Aesthetics: A Selected Annotated Bibliography: Books and Articles in the English Language </em>(New York: Humanities Press, 1973) &ndash; good up to 1970 </p>
  <p> Tom Bottomore and Laurence Harris, eds., <em>A Dictionary of Marxist Thought</em> (Oxford: Blackwell, 1991) &ndash; invaluable dictionary of concepts, words etc.: v. useful reference work </p>
  <p> Leszek Kolakowski, <em>Main Currents of Marxism</em>, 3 vols (Oxford: OUP, 1978) &ndash; depressingly cold war in some of its authorial posturing, but useful as a survey of main lines of classical Marxism </p>
  <p> David McLellan, <em>Karl Marx: Selected Writings</em>, 2 nd edition (Oxford: OUP, 2000) &ndash; excellent one volume selection of excerpts of all the key texts: well worth owning. </p>
  <p> David McLellan, <em>Karl Marx: His Life and Thought</em> (London: Macmillan, 1973)&shy; &ndash; scholarly biog </p>
  <p> David McLellan, <em>The Thought of Karl Marx: An Introduction</em> (London: Macmillan, 1971): useful anthology offering a chronological and thematic survey through well-chosen bites </p>
  <p> Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels, <em>On Literature and Art</em> (Moscow: Progress, 1976) &ndash; anthology of pretty much all the fragments etc. in which Marx and Engels comment on literature </p>
  <p> S.S. Prawer, <em>Karl Marx and World Literature</em> (Oxford: OUP, 1978) &ndash; useful critical survey of all Marx&rsquo;s scattered remarks and comments on literature, though not itself Marxist in methodology. </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Anthologies: </strong></p>
  <p> Francis Barker et al., <em>Literature, Politics and theory: Papers from the Essex Conference, 1976-84</em> (London: Methuen, 1986) </p>
  <p> David Craig, <em>Marxists on Literature: an anthology</em> (Harmondsworth: Penguin, 1975) </p>
  <p> \Chris Kraus and Sylvere Lotringer, eds., <em>Hatred of Capitalism: A Semiotext(e) Reader</em> (Los Angeles: Semiotext(e), 2001) </p>
  <p> Berel Lang and Forrest Williams, eds., <em>Marxism and Art</em> (New York, 1972) </p>
  <p> Bernd Magnus, Cesare Casarino and Rebecca E Karl, eds., <em>Marxism Beyond Marxism</em> (London: Routledge, 1996), esp. Fredric Jameson, &lsquo;Actually Existing Marxism&rsquo;, pp. 13-54 </p>
  <p> Francis Mulhern, ed. <em>Contemporary Marxist Literary Criticism</em> (London: Longman, 1992) </p>
  <p> Cary Nelson and Lawrence Grossberg, eds. <em>Marxism and the Interpretation of Culture</em>, (Urbana and Chicago, 1988) </p>
  <p> Rudich Norman, ed. <em>Weapons of Criticism: Marxism in America and the Literary Tradition</em> (Palo Alto, California, 1976) </p>
  <p> Lydia Sargent, ed., <em>The Unhappy Marriage of Marxism &amp; Feminism</em> (London: Pluto, 1986) </p>
  <p> Ellen Meiksins Wood and John Bellamy, eds., <em>In Defense of History: Marxism and the Postmodern Agenda</em> (New York: Monthly Review Press, 1997) </p>
  <p> Maynard Solomon, ed., <em>Marxism and Art: Essays Classic and Contemporary</em> (New York, 1973) </p>
  <p>&nbsp; </p>
  <p><strong> Assorted forms of contemporary Marxist criticism / post-Marxism and the present: </strong></p>
  <p> T.W. Adorno, <em>Aesthetic Theory</em>, trans. Robert Hullot-Kentor, eds. Gretel Adorno and Rold Tiedemann (Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 1997) </p>
  <p> Stanley Aronowitz, <em>The Crisis in Historical Materialism: Class, Politics, and Culture in Marxist Theory</em> (South Hadley, Mass: J.F. Bergin, 1981) </p>
  <p> Ronald Aronson, <em>After Marxism</em> (New York: Guilford, 1995) </p>
  <p> Jean Baudrillard, <em>For a Critique of the Political Economy of the Sign</em> (St. Louis: Telos, 1981); and <em>The Mirror of Production</em>, trans. Mark Poster (St. Louis: Telos, 1975) </p>
  <p> Timothy Bewes, <em>Cynicism and Postmodernity</em> (London: Verso, 1997) </p>
  <p> Terrell Carver, <em>The Postmodern Marx</em> (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 1998) </p>
  <p> G.A. Cohen, <em>Karl Marx&rsquo;s Theory of History: A Defence</em> (Oxford: Clarendon, 1978) </p>
  <p> Peter Dews, <em>The Limits of Disenchantment</em> (London: Verso, 1995) </p>
  <p> Terry Eagleton, <em>Ideology of the Aesthetic</em> (Oxford: Blackwell, 1990) </p>
  <p> John Elster, <em>Making Sense of Marx</em> (Cambridge: C.U.P., 1985) </p>
  <p> Michel Foucault, <em>Remarks on Marx</em> (New York: Semiotext(e), 1991) </p>
  <p> John Frow, <em>Cultural Studies &amp; Cultural Value</em> (Oxford: Blackwell, 1995) </p>
  <p> Jean-Joseph Goux, <em>Symbolic Economies: After Marx and Freud</em>, trans. Jennifer Curtiss Gage (Ithaca, New York: Cornell University Press, 1990) </p>
  <p> Michael Hardt and Antonio Negri, <em>Empire</em> (Cambridge, Mass; Harvard UP, 2000) </p>
  <p> George Hartley, <em>The Abyss of Representation: Marxism and the Postmodern Sublime</em> (Durham: Duke University Press, 2003) </p>
  <p> David Harvey, <em>The New Imperialism</em> (Oxford: OUP, 2003) </p>
  <p> Moyra Haslett, <em>Marxist Literary and Cultural Studies</em> (London: Macmilllan, 2000) </p>
  <p> Jean E. Howard and Scott Cutler Shershow, edsl., <em>Marxist Shakespeares</em> (London: Routledge, 2001) </p>
  <p> Naomi Klein, <em>No Logo</em> (New York: Picador, 2000) &shy;&ndash; Marxism lite / journalism but suggestive </p>
  <p> Franco Moretti, <em>Signs Taken For Wonders: Essays in the Sociology of Literary Forms</em>, trans. Susan Fischer, David Forgacs and David Miller (London: Verso, 1983) </p>
  <p> Francis Mulhern, <em>The present lasts a long time: essays in cultural politics</em> (Cork: Cork University Press, in association with Field Day, 1998) </p>
  <p> R.S. Neale, <em>Writing Marxist History: British Society, Economy &amp; Culture since 1700</em> (Oxford: Blackwell, 1985) </p>
  <p> Christopher Prenderghast, ed., <em>Cultural Materialism: On Raymond Williams</em> (London: University of Minnesota Press, 1995) </p>
  <p> Stuart Sim, ed., <em>Post-Marxism: A Reader</em> (Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1998) </p>
  <p> Michael Sprinker, <em>History and Ideology in Proust: &lsquo;A la recherche du temps perdu&rsquo;, and the Third French Republic</em> (London: Verso, 1998) </p>
  <p> Robert Paul Wolff, <em>Moneybags Must Be So Lucky: On the Literary Structure of &ldquo;Capital&rdquo;</em> (Amherst: University of Massachusetts Press, 1988) </p>
  <p> Eugene Victor Wolfenstein, <em>Pyschoanalytic-Marxism Groundwork</em> (New York and London: Guilford Press / Free Association Books, 1993) </p>
  <p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
  <p><strong> Selected further reading: </strong></p>
  <p><strong> Session 1: </strong></p>
  <p> Michael Sprinker, ed., <em>Ghostly Demarcations: A Symposium on Jacques Derrida&rsquo;s &lsquo;Specters of Marx&rsquo;</em> (London: Verso, 1999) &ndash; survey of responses to Derrida, including Derrida&rsquo;s reply to critics , &lsquo;Marx &amp; Sons&rsquo;, pp. 213-269 </p>
  <p> Gareth Stedman Jones, &lsquo;The Marxism of the Early Lukacs&rsquo;, <em>Western Marxism: A Critical Reader</em>, ed. New Left Review (London: Verso, 1977), pp. 11-60 </p>
  <p> Georg Lukacs, <em>A Defence of </em>History and Class Consciousnes, trans. Esther Leslie, with an introduction by John Rees and a postface by Slavoj Zizek (London: Verso, 2000) </p>
  <p> Maurice Merleau-Ponty, <em>Adventures of the Dialectic</em>, trans. J. Bien (London, 1974), esp. chapter on &lsquo;Western Marxism&rsquo;, pp. 30-58 (in <em>Modern Critical Thought</em>, ed. Drew Milne, pp. 81-103) </p>
  <p> Drew Milne, &lsquo;Marxist Literary Theory after Derrida&rsquo;, <em>Common Sense</em>, no 19 (1996), pp. 5-19. </p>
  <p><strong> &nbsp;</strong></p>
  <p><strong> Session 2: </strong></p>
  <p> Etienne Balibar, <em>The Philosophy of Marx</em>, trans. Chris Turner (London: Verso, 1995) </p>
  <p> Stanley Aronowitz, <em>The Crisis in Historical Materialism: Class, Politics, and Culture in Marxist Theory</em> (South Hadley, Mass: J.F. Bergin, 1981) </p>
  <p> Alex Callinicos, <em>Marxism and Philosophy </em>(Oxford: OUP, 1983) </p>
  <p> Mark Cowling, <em>The Communist Manifesto: New Interpretations</em> (Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1998) </p>
  <p> Raymond Williams, <em>Marxism and Literature</em> (Oxford: OUP, 1977) </p>
  <p><strong> &nbsp;</strong></p>
  <p><strong> Session 3:</strong><strong></strong></p>
  <p> Theodor Adorno, &lsquo;Reconciliation under Duress&rsquo;, in <em>Aesthetics and Politics</em>, Ernst Bloch et al (London: Verso, 1977), pp. 151-176; also in Adorno, <em>Notes to Literature</em>, vol. 1 (Adorno&rsquo;s stinging critique of Lukacs&rsquo; later work) </p>
  <p> Thomas M. Kemple, <em>Reading Marx Writing: Melodrama, the Market, and the &lsquo;Grundrisse&rsquo;</em> (Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1995) - an alternative way of reading Marx </p>
  <p> Leon Trotsky, <em>Literature and Revolution</em> (Ann Arbor, 1960) </p>
  <p> David Craig, <em>Marxists on Literature: an anthology</em> (Harmondsworth: Penguin, 1975) </p>
  <p> David Forgacs, &lsquo;Marxist Literary Theories&rsquo;, <em>Modern Literary Theory: a comparative introduction</em>, eds. Ann Jefferson and David Robey (London: Batsford, 1986) &ndash; good survey essay </p>
  <p> Dave Laing, <em>The Marxist Theory of Art: An Introductory Survey</em> (Sussex: Harvester, 1978) </p>
  <p> Cliff Slaughter, <em>Marxism, Ideology &amp; Literature</em> (London: Macmillan, 1980) </p>
  <p><strong> &nbsp;</strong></p>
  <p><strong> Session 4: </strong></p>
  <p> Theodor W. Adorno, &lsquo;On the Fetish Character of Music and the Regression of Listening&rsquo;, <em>The Essential Frankfurt School Reader</em>, eds. Andrew Arato &amp; Eike Gebhardt (Oxford: Blackwell, 1978), pp. 270-299 </p>
  <p> Theodor W. Adorno and Walter Benjamin, <em>The Complete Correspondecne 1928-1940</em>, ed. Henri Lonitz, trans. Nicholas Walker (Cambridge: Polity, 1999) </p>
  <p> Walter Benjamin, &lsquo;The Work of Art in the Age of Its Technological Reproducibility&rsquo; (Third Version), <em>Walter Benjamin: Selected Writings, vol 4: 1938-1940</em>, trans. Edmund Jephcott and Others, eds. Howard Eiland and Michael W. Jennings (Cambridge, Mass: Harvard University Press, 2003), pp. 251-83. [Also as &lsquo;The Work of Art in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction&rsquo; in Walter Benjamin, <em>Illuminations</em>, ed. Hannah Arendt, trans. Harry Zohn (London: Fontana, 1972), pp. 219-254. </p>
  <p><em> Brecht on Theatre, </em> trans. John Willett (London: Methuen, 1964) </p>
  <p> Howard Caygill, <em>Walter Benjamin: The colour of experience</em> (London: Routledge, 1998) </p>
  <p> T.J. Clark, <em>Farewell to an Idea: Episodes from a History of Modernism</em> (New Haven: Yale University Press, 1999) </p>
  <p> David Frisby, <em>Fragments of Modernity</em> (Cambridge, 1985) </p>
